Would love to see more discussion around not just symptoms of ADHD but about how being undiagnosed and unaware can lead to this us hiding behind masking & unhealthy strategies that appear like they’re just anxiety on the surface (leading to those misdiagnoses of anxiety tbh).

And this thing where we create strategies that are unhealthy & intrusive on our lives is so normalised over a lifetime too. So there are probably so many people walking around who might have even seen ADHD content who have ADHD but think they must not as they’re “good” with time.

So of course it turns into constant anxiety that I’ve missed things. Habitually using and checking my phone calendar. 18473 phone alarms. Dedicating my whole day to not being late for something in the evening. Overestimating time and losing out on time for me. Bad strategies.

Often it’s that I was trained that issues relating to what I now understand as ADHD weren’t acceptable. Being late isn’t okay and I’d get in trouble for it. Missing appointments means a fee or I miss out. Making people wait for me is rude. 28 years of training to not miss times.

A lot of Discovering my ADHD has been me questioning “Am I MORE proactive about this than what’s healthy?” “Have I always been like this?” “Why do I feel I have to behave this way?” “What’s the insecurity behind this intrusive behaviour/thinking?”

And again - thank god for people who have already been diagnosed and through this shit with their therapists sharing this info online via memes & tweets & TikToks because I wouldn’t have been able to start detangling my relationship with time to understand it this way without.

This is one of those things that I initially was like “nah that doesn’t apply to me” when I started relating to ADHD symptoms & checked ADHD out deeper. I think more people would seek help if they could see that being undiagnosed for decades can lead to hindering strategies too.

Essentially I don’t trust myself with time and this leads to me responding to that in ways that impact me lots. Took a while for me to untangle that me being overly cautious about time and obsessively aware to it sometimes actually was a ✨response✨ to time blindness.
